A fisheye lens, maybe that's a bit too much for a birdhouse.
You learn from your mistakes.
I should have known, considering I already made one with a "normal" lens.
I'll tell you more this weekend once I've installed the second one I made.
Let's say the birds will have a better Internet connection than mine in 2015.
Or at least, that's the goal.
The box that already contains a nest box is using the home Wi-Fi.
There is still work to be done to connect the other one.
Well, I hung the other nest box during the day. Here's what it looks like in a good place in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?", I don't hear someone asking.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I recovered from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has a strange shape, it's because of the rotating side panel of the bird feeder. I bought it like that and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my setup around it.
As there is no electricity in the garden, the whole system is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a photo of the panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the bird feeder houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of power.
I call that a feature. That way birds can also have a bit of privacy.
At first, I didn't know if the Internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have sufficed.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to mount a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and point it down towards the garden.
I could always do it when I install more camera nest boxes, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
Now, for reasons that escape me for now, the camera is offline. It turned off barely an hour after sunset.
The battery charge might have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Perhaps it wasn't able to charge fully in a little less than half a day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a battery telemetry system. I might add one during a future revision.
A few more sensors would be nice, I think.
And maybe a battery capable of lasting the whole night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fisheye is way too much.
But I'm already looking at parts on Digikey, so I might just make a custom PCB for this use case.
Or not. We'll see.
And, it's still offline.
Super.
Given the solar panels installed on the house, the sun is really high only for about 90 minutes.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens or not.
Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
In fact, on the USB-C board I was using to connect the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I swapped the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP did not connect immediately, let's wait a few minutes.
One hour later: still offline.
It seems like it is restarting in a loop and triggering Tasmota's reset functionality.
I think the board is just faulty. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it will work.
Look what I found in the workshop.
A 24 V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly hidden by a tree) that it drops back down to almost nothing as soon as I use it.
I think I'll wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this installation or if I need the best panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So, either something is wrong with this panel or with my multimeter, or they have changed the specs.
Good news, everyone!
They changed the specifications and the one I have is H.S.
The titles of the old and new specifications mention a 12 V, 10 W panel.
That's why I don't delete my old e-mails.
Hey, look: the thing reconnected for about half a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of power. It would have only taken a little over two hours.
Guess what: the weather is cloudy today. So I'm not sure that this solar panel (probably broken) is capable of generating enough energy to do anything.
Let's wait and see.
Latest news: I installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
Who knows, maybe everything will shut down at sunset, but let's wait and see.
By the way, I'm using the ping integration in Home Assistant to monitor whether it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not so bad.
